com.gtnewhorizon.structurelib.structure

Interface IStructureElement<T>

  • All Known Subinterfaces:
    IStructureElementChain<T>, IStructureElementCheckOnly<T>, IStructureElementDeferred<T>, IStructureElementNoPlacement<T>

    public interface IStructureElement<T>
    Use StructureUtility to instantiate. These are the building blocks for your IStructureDefinition. It represents what a particular element can be and how this particular element should be autoplaced.

        Deprecated. caller should call the non deprecated overload. implementor for reusable IStructureElement should still implement this. implementor for private implementations can freely ignore this as long as you know the caller will not call this overload.
        Try place the block by taking resource from given IItemSource.

        You might want to use StructureUtility.survivalPlaceBlock(Block, int, World, int, int, int, IItemSource, net.minecraft.entity.player.EntityPlayer) or its overloads to implement this.

        Parameters:
        trigger - trigger item
        s - drain resources from this place
        actor - source of action. for very critical errors you can also just send the error messages here, bypassing any filter that chatter might have.
        chatter - send error messages here. Caller will choose an appropriate way to forward it to player if the other fallbacks also fails.

      • getBlocksToPlace

        @Nullable
default IStructureElement.BlocksToPlace getBlocksToPlace(T t,
                                                                   World world,
                                                                   int x,
                                                                   int y,
                                                                   int z,
                                                                   ItemStack trigger,
                                                                   AutoPlaceEnvironment env)
        A simplified version of survivalPlaceBlock. Return null if not implemented.

        BY OVERRIDING THIS TO NULL, YOU ACKNOWLEDGE THAT THE check(Object, World, int, int, int) OF THIS CLASS IS SIDE EFFECT FREE AND CAN HAVE ITS CHECK CALLED WITHOUT BREAKING ANYTHING. OTHERWISE OVERRIDE THE survivalPlaceBlock(Object, World, int, int, int, ItemStack, AutoPlaceEnvironment) TO PROVIDE A SIDEEFFECT FREE IStructureElement.PlaceResult.SKIP.

        It should be noticed that this filter is only advisory and the actual survivalPlaceBlock(Object, World, int, int, int, ItemStack, AutoPlaceEnvironment) or check(Object, World, int, int, int) are free to reject/accept/place blocks not contained in this list, e.g. when the element can be placed anywhere in the structure, but no more than 3 overall; when the structure element cannot know all blocks it will accept at the time of calling; when this is backed by a legacy IStructureElement that just didn't implement this API.

        Parameters:
        trigger - trigger item
        env - autoplacing environment
        Returns:
        null if not implemented, otherwise an instance describing what kind of blocks will be placed by survivalPlaceBlock(Object, World, int, int, int, ItemStack, AutoPlaceEnvironment)

      • survivalPlaceBlock

        default IStructureElement.PlaceResult survivalPlaceBlock(T t,
                                                         World world,
                                                         int x,
                                                         int y,
                                                         int z,
                                                         ItemStack trigger,
                                                         AutoPlaceEnvironment env)
        Try place the block by taking resource from given IItemSource.

        You might want to use StructureUtility.survivalPlaceBlock(Block, int, World, int, int, int, IItemSource, net.minecraft.entity.player.EntityPlayer) or its overloads to implement this.

        The default implementation provided will

        1. Get IStructureElement.BlocksToPlace via getBlocksToPlace(Object, World, int, int, int, ItemStack, AutoPlaceEnvironment). If not null
          1. call check(Object, World, int, int, int). If this returns true, IStructureElement.PlaceResult.SKIP will be returned without further action.
          2. Use the IStructureElement.BlocksToPlace retrieved earlier and passed in IItemSource to determine an item to place
          3. Hand over control to StructureUtility#survivalPlaceBlock(ItemStack, NBTMode, NBTTagCompound, boolean, World, int, int, int, IItemSource, EntityPlayer, Consumer)
        2. Call legacy survivalPlaceBlock(Object, World, int, int, int, ItemStack, IItemSource, EntityPlayerMP, Consumer) if env.getActor() contains an EntityPlayerMP
        3. Emit warning under debug mode (or throw exception under panic mode), then return IStructureElement.PlaceResult.SKIP
        It should be noticed that the default implementation is likely to cause unexpected issues if the check(Object, World, int, int, int) is not side effect free, or is not idempotent. E.g. the check(Object, World, int, int, int) will add current coord to a List. As this method might be invoked at a location that is already accepted, this will cause the machine to have multiple of this coord in its list.
        Parameters:
        trigger - trigger item
        env - autoplacing environment
